es © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Graveron-Sémerville in Eure (Normandy), from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigimar</i> (see   Siemer  ) + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. The surname was taken to Scotland in the 12th century by William <i>de Somerville</i>, a retainer of David, Earl of Huntingdon, who became King David I of Scotland.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Somacháin</b> (see   Summers  ) or <b>Mag Shamradháin</b> (see   Somers  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Siemer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Helmuth, Otto, Theresia.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Siegmar</i>, composed of the elements <i>sigi</i> ‘victory’ + <i>mari</i>, <i>meri</i> ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Sommerville","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Somerville   1."]},{"name":"Summerville","meanings":["English, Scottish (Lanarkshire), and Irish: variant of   Somerville  . This form of the surname is particularly common in Ireland."]},{"name":"Simrell","meanings":["Scottish: perhaps related to the Ulster name<b>Sumeril</b>, a variant of   Somerville  ."]},{"name":"Summerfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’ + <i>feld</i> ‘field, open land’, denoting summer pasture or fields cultivated only in summer, such as Summerfield in Woodnesborough (Kent), Somerfield Court in Sellindge (Kent), and Summerfield in Marlborough (Wiltshire).","English: variant of   Somerville  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Sommerfeld  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"wife William de Somerville of Lanarkshire married William de Somerville before 1161, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1161–Male":"1161–Surnud","1183–1215":"1183–1215","–Female":"Surnud","about 1161":"umbes 1161","1215":"1215","before 1161":"enne 1161","1140":"1140","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Europe":"Europe","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1161–Male":"1161–Kuollut","1183–1215":"1183–1215","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1161":"noin 1161","1215":"1215","before 1161":"ennen vuotta 1161","1140":"1140","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Europe":"Europe","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","1161–Male":"1161–Décédé","1183–1215":"1183–1215","–Female":"Décédée","about 1161":"environ 1161","1215":"1215","before 1161":"avant 1161","1140":"1140","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Écosse","Europe":"Europe","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"wife William de Somerville of Lanarkshire a épousé William de Somerville avant 1161, à Europe. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1140–Male":"1140–Verstorben","1161–Male":"1161–Versto